<i>"Good... Bad... I'm the guy with the fire elemental."</i><br><i>"Shop Smart. Shop Ez-Mart!"</i><br></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> Seleen</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#333333>(12/4/00 6:10:07 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerlibrarysubmissions.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=14.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Mages</span><hr size=1> Mages really are a great class to play. Most of what you are hearing is the natural griping that occurs when change happens. Verant recently fixed some bugs about our pets and since they were beneficial bugs, folks hated to see them fixed.<br>
<br>
Also keep in mind, no one ever posts when they are happy ... they're too busy playing *grin*. So it is only natural to only see complaints posted.<br>
<br>
I've been playing a mage a long time now and never regretted it.<br>
<br>
You asked about what are the mjor drawback(s) to a mage. Well ... first you need to understand our strengths. Our characters are pure offensive power ... we deal more damage during a typical fight than anyone. Wizards can deal faster damage and Necros can deal more damage over long periods of time ... but for the typical group fight, nothing beats a mage.<br>
<br>
The balance for all this offensive power is no defense. Mages are totally dependent on their pet to keep the monster away from them. If the pet dies, so will you. So the key to playing a mage is knowing what you can handle and how to avoid aggroing the monster onto you. Some mages never do learn that trick so they get frustrated.<br>
<br>
Anyway ... try one and see if it is your style. A mage is not meant for everyone but if you like being able to solo as well as having a lot to offer a group, it may be what you're looking for.<br>
<br>
Seleen yan`Sael<br>
Tarew Marr <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uartiethebold.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Artie the Bold</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://brotherhood.rpg-guilds.com/artie/artie10x10.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Elementalist</span><br>  Posts: 45<br> <font color=#333333>(12/4/00 7:38:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerlibrarysubmissions.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=14.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://brotherhood.rpg-guilds.com/artie/Artie.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Mages</span><hr size=1> First of all, stay away from the official EQ boards. They're poison. Most of what you'll see on there are rants and flames that started way back when, due to (in my opinion) Verant not knowing how to communicate with its customers, and a large portion of the posting customers not knowing how to get their concerns across to Verant. It's been snowballing ever since.<br>
<br>
Now, to address your real issue of whether or not to play the mage, in what capacity I can.<br>
<br>
I'm not going to talk about 'power' since there are so many variations of that in the game. Mages are good at offense. When I was 20th level (enchanter) I saw a 17th level mage soloing a creature that I could not take down alone. That is one type of power. As an enchanter, I cannot tell you how many lives I have saved (my own included) by stopping a fight cold and making the bad guys just stand there and forget who they were mad at. It doesn't kill anything, but is also a type of power. Clerics bring you back from the dead and restore some experience lost at death. *drool*. You get the idea. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
The mage class has a lot going for it. In a fight with any mob (short for mobile npc ... er npc is short for non-player character) that the mage has any business fighting, the mage will win. Damage output is what the mage does well, through a combination of pets and spells.<br>
<br>
Pets are wonderful, as they are a resource that only costs you mana once for unilimited damage, for as long as you keep it alive that is. Also, for as long as they keep a mob off of you, you can consider them a hit point buffer as well. Mages, like all INT-based casters, are fragile.<br>
<br>
Direct damage spells are respectable as well. While not as good as a wizard's in terms of damage per minute, they are very good in their own right. Also, while some other casting classes are vulnerable when they run out of mana, the mage still has his pet to provide some protection or buy time to escape if needed.<br>
<br>
Mages are also very self-sufficient, with the ability to summon food, water, bandages, and weapons. The weapons themselves are not great, but at certain levels are very nice for pets, and some have spell effects that are fun and sometimes useful.<br>
<br>
Like everything else, though, there are drawbacks.<br>
<br>
Mages are very dependent on having a pet to survive. So you must use caution when traveling, in dungeons, when you log on, etc.<br>
<br>
Downtime when a mage logs on is high. Much of what a mage does is invest mana through summonings. This includes pets, food/water, weapons, bandages, and utility items. Some things you can get around, like buying food/water/bandages from a vendor, but others are required, such as pets and even heatstones/coldstones for party members who cannot see at night.<br>
<br>
Linkdeath carries a high price for mages. Going linkdead means your connection to the EQ servers has become unstable. When this happens, you are booted from the game. When you return, anything that was in your inventory that was summoned will be gone. Pets also die if you go linkdead. This carries with it the same downtime as the above point, so if your connection is not very stable you may want to consider another class.<br>
<br>
The mage class has a lack of variety. Each spell circle brings more of the same ... new pets, new damage spells, new summoned items, etc. The upgrades are very nice in most cases, but in most spell levels you won't get any 'new' abilities, with a few exceptions such as summoning a ring of flight, etc.<br>
<br>
All that said, remember the one beautiful thing about EverQuest ... you are not locked in to a single character. Definitely play around with other classes. I say this for two reasons:<br>
<br>
1.) Without first-hand experience with other classes, you won't have a true idea of what is fun for YOU.<br>
<br>
2.) Sooner or later, you will group with people. Having an idea of what the capabilities of your teammates are has benefits that I can't even begin to describe here.<br>
<br>
3.) Okay, I said two reasons but there's really a third. You may like several classes. If so, play them all at your discretion. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
I think I've rambled on long enough. Give it a try. If you like it, great, and if not, keep trying classes until you find one you like. There are 14 of them, and at least one should appeal to any given person. Lord knows I've played (and still play) enough of the classes to know. <p><body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">

